<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-199-924  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 199 924.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Personal Computing  May 1989 v13 n5 p84(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Avoiding virus hysteria. (computer virus) (includes a relatedarticle on viruses in Russia)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Honan, Patrick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The dilemma facing computer network administrators today is theprotection of the integrity of the network and validity of datafrom virus attack without unduly restricting users.andP;  The networkat the Jet Propulsion Laboratory suffered four virus attacks in1988, which were traced to software obtained from computerbulleting boards, including CompuServe and Genie.andP;  JPL managementdecided that, rather than restrict bulletin board use, they wouldstress the importance of frequent backups and recommend testingsoftware before running on the facility systems.andP;  Viruses have thepotential to seriously damage sensitive data and severely hamperoperations.andP;  Symptoms include slowed operation, unrequested diskaccess, and less available memory.andP;  A summary of virus protectionprograms is included.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VirusesPreventive MaintenanceNetworksComputer Virus Industry AssociationSecurity Software.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   A virus protection sampler. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>